 from Middle English <i>atte west tun(e)</i> ‘at the west farmstead, settlement’ (Old English <i>west</i> + <i>tūn</i>), or from Middle English <i>(bi) weste(n)tune</i> (Old English <i>be westan tūne</i> or <i>be west in tūne</i>), denoting someone who lived either to the west of a settlement or in the western part of a settlement. The latter was a common surname in Sussex."],"variants":[{"name":"Wesson","meanings":["English (Midlands and Kent): variant of   Weston  .","History: John Wesson came from England to Salem, MA, in 1644."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Weston was born in 1275, in Warnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, William De Weston, was 41 and his mother, Joan de Pontisse, was 20. He married Maud Westcott in 1305, in Shere, Surrey, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1320, in Wiston, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1275–1320":"1275–1320","1270–1360":"1270–1360","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1297–1337":"1297–1337","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1235–1288":"1235–1288","1255–1345":"1255–1345","1275":"1275","1297":"1297","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1235":"1235","1278":"1278","1288":"1288","1255":"1255","1320":"1320","about 1297":"umbes 1297","Warnham, Horsham, Sussex, England":"Warnham, Sussex, Inglismaa, United King